													
													PASSPORTJS:

â­ï¸ required libraries that passportjs works in conjuction with :
	- express-session
	- express-flash
 
â­ï¸ Three methods(for initializing passport):
	1. passport.use
	2. passport.serialize
	3. passport.deserialize

1ï¸âƒ£ï¸. passport.use
	âš¡ï¸ syntax: passport.use(new <Strategy_type>(optoins ,authenticate))
	âš¡ï¸ example:
		passport.use(
				new LocalStrategy(
					{
						usernameField: "email",    //ğŸ—’ï¸ Specifies the field name(in the HTML form) for the username (default is 'username')
						passwordField: "password", //ğŸ—’ï¸ Specifies the field name(in the HTML form) for the password (default is 'password')
					},
					authenticate:(email,password,done)=>done()
				)
			);

		ğŸª§ï¸ authenticate:   this is where you find the user with it's credentials like email & password,
							and if found, return the done function with the found-user as it's second argument.
			
		ğŸª§ï¸ done() can be called with three arguments:
					1- null
					2- foundUser or false, if user not found
					3- error-message, if user not found

2ï¸âƒ£ï¸. passport.serialize((user,done) => done())
	This function is used to determine what data from the user object should be stored in the session. 
	Its primary purpose is to take a user object as an argument and serialize it into a format that can 
	be stored in the session. 
	
3ï¸âƒ£ï¸. passport.deserialize((user,done) => done())
	 It takes the data stored in the session (in this case, the id serialized earlier) and uses it to retrieve 
	 the user object from your database or wherever your user data is stored.

â­ï¸ Initialization:
	app.use(passport.initialize());
	app.use(passport.session());
	//ğŸ—’ï¸ Initialize Passport and configure it to use sessions
	
	app.use(flash()) //ğŸ—’ï¸ passport use express-flash to flash error messages.
	app.use(
		session({
			secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET,
			resave: false,
			saveUninitialized: false,
		})
	);  //ğŸ—’ï¸ passport relies on express-session to store and retrieve session data.

â­ï¸ Implementation:

	we use it as "middleware":

	âš¡ï¸ syntax: app.<method>("/<route>", passport.authenticate(<strategy>,options), (req, res) => {});

	âš¡ï¸example: 
		app.post(
			"/login",
			passport.authenticate("local", {
				successRedirect: "/user",  // redirect route on success
				failureRedirect: "/login", // redirect route on failure
				failureFlash: true,  // flashes any error message(messages set in the authenticate function, on failure)
			}),
			(req,res)=>{ /* if you want to send any stuff*/ }
		);

